======================================== NETWORK DEVICES ========================================

1) Hosts are any device which requests data from some other device.
2) Servers are any device which can send data upon request.
3) IP Addresses are are the identity of every Host(1) - similar to a street address: Country.State.City.Street.House 
4) Networks transport traffic between hosts. If two computers are connected, then this constitutes a network.
   - Networks are a grouping of hosts.
5) Sub-Networks (Subnets) are the logical grouping of hosts. For instance, routers create sub-networks.
   - Subnets are logical grouping of interconnected network devices. The subdivision of a network into smaller networks helps to 
improve network performance and security. Devices on the same subnet have IP addresses that fall within the same range as defined by a 
subnet mask.
6) Repeaters are there to ensure that data doesn't deteriorate/diminish during travel. If two hosts are far away from each other, data 
decays during travel. To prevent this, repeaters repeat the data and "fix" or "re-generate" it which allows them to continue to 
travel far.
   - This allows for hosts to be far away from each other.
   - The scaling is not linear:
     N: Number of Hosts
     M_[N]: Number of Connections for N Hosts
     M_0 = 0
     Formula: (N-1) + (M_[N-1]) = M_[N]
     Example2:
     N = 1
     (1-1) + (M_0) = M_1
     ** 0 = M_1 **
     N = 2
     (2-1) + (M_1) = M_2
     (1) + (0) = M_2
     If, there is only one host: No connections to other hosts.
     If, there is two hosts: One connection between the hosts.
     Other formula = Edges = N * (N-1) / 2
7) Hubs are, simply put, a multi-port repeater. Hubs also re-generate data. If a host sends data to the hub, the hub then sends out all 
of the re-generated (fresh) data to the remaining hosts.
   - Hubs also facilitate scaling. 
   - The scaling is linear. Only one new connection per new computer. Edges = N
8) Bridges sit between hub-connected networks. They also only have two ports. They are also able to learn which computers 
sit on which side of the bridge.
   - A bridge has two sides: Side "A" and side "B". Computers on side A have to go through the bridge to get to side B. 
   - Bridges are able to "learn" on which side the computer sits, thus improving efficiency of the network.


